  "text": ") when compared to the large intestine (10 11 -10 12 CFU mL [CITATION_1] . However, our analysis using qPCR did not reveal a significant difference in bacterial density when comparing the proximal and distal GIT of dairy calves and chicken. The estimated total bacterial numbers by qPCR revealed a much higher population in the small intestinal tract of calves, suggesting that more uncultured species reside in small intestine. The low number of chickens analyzed may also have limited the analysis sensitivity for bacterial density. Future studies with a larger number of birds may be required to accurately determine whether significant regional differences exist in bacterial density in the GIT of chicken.",
